==English==

===Etymology===
Possibly a corruption of [[cage]].

===Pronunciation===
*[[IPA]]: /kædʒ/
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ædʒ|-ædʒ]]

===Noun===
'''cadge'''
# a circular [[frame]] on which [[cadgers]] carry [[hawks]] for sale.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|cadges|'''[[cadging]]''' ''or'' '''[[cadgin]]'''|cadged|cadged}}
# {{cattag|Geordie}} to [[beg]].
#: ''"Are ye gannin te [[cadge]] a lift of yoer fatha?"''
# {{cattag|US|UK|slang}} to obtain something by [[wit]] or [[guile]]; to [[convince]] someone to do something they might not normally do.
#:'''1897''' ''So Donkin, unrebuked, cursed enough for two, '''cadged''' for matches, borrowed tobacco, and loafed for hours, very much at home before the stove.'' — Joseph Conrad, ''The Nigger of the Narcissus'' [http://etext.virginia.edu/etcbin/ot2www-pubeng?specfile=/texts/english/modeng/publicsearch/modengpub.o2w&act=surround&offset=173781723&tag=Conrad,+Joseph,+1857-1924:+The+Nigger+of+the+Narcissus,+1897&query=cadge&id=ConNarc Chapter 5.]''
# {{archaic}} to carry [[hawks]] and other [[birds]] of [[prey]].

